And so there came the Carpool Challenge, a rallying cry to stir the hearts once more, a March campaign swift and bright and it did bring forth an increase, though the challenge remained as before, how to sustain the breath of life in this endeavor against the tides of indifference and the rhythms of the academic calendar.

Yet there was another truth, buried deep, the love of the open road and the solitary freedom it promised. The car, a symbol of independence, unyielding in its cultural roots. Incentives were offered, tokens of gratitude in the form of gift cards, small treasures for the weary traveler, to the local stores and cafes, a balm for the soul. But one wonders what greater prizes might have wrought, a bicycle perhaps, or the promise of a hybrid or electric car. These fantasies might have drawn forth those who hesitated, kindling a new fire where the old had waned. The prizes, unchanging, might have held more allure had they grown in worth with each passing month. To announce in the heart of December a grand reward would have surely quickened the pace of those who had grown tired. One can only ponder what might have been, had the stakes been raised and the call to action resounded more fervently amidst the cold and quiet of the year’s end.

In the gloom of the Library of Congress, I found myself poring over the early Edison films, drawn to their trickery like a moth to a forgotten flame. Fifteen they were, from the dying whispers of the nineteenth century to the first murmurs of the twentieth. Films that played with the mind's eye, slipping reality through the cracks of the reel with a sleight of hand born of clever editing. My journey through these shadows aimed to uncover the poetic threads binding these films, and to sift through the dust for those rare gems that dared to step beyond their time-worn bounds. 

At the turn of the century, most trick films were bound to their sets, framed by the rigid proscenium, the camera a watchful sentinel that never moved, holding fast to its creed of one shot, one film. Yet, there were those brave few that inched towards the dawn of a new era, introducing a dance of multiple shots that whispered of change.

What they shared, these trick films, was a devotion to the interior, a stage where the camera stood steadfast. No pursuit of figures, no shift in view, for the lens was rooted in its theatrical past, echoing the vaudeville and magic acts that had preceded it. Movement was but a lateral waltz, a side-to-side glide with no venture towards the audience. Consider Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), where actors drift from the right, skimming the stage like ghosts, never drawing the camera from its fixed gaze.

The proscenium's embrace meant long shots reigned supreme, with medium shots as rare companions, and the intimacy of close-ups was a stranger. The theater's influence was strong, its essence distilled into every frame, where the audience's gaze was framed by the stage's boundary. Actors held their ground, neither advancing nor retreating, leaving the close-up an untapped well.

In those early days, trick films held to the notion that one conceptual shot was a film entire. A constraint that kept their tales brief, their magic confined to a minute's breath, dictated by the frames per second. Their narratives were simple conjurings, vanishing acts, and clever exchanges without the weight of story. Yet, within the illusion of a single shot, lay the hidden seams of multiple, stitched together to conjure apparitions. Take The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). At first glance, a seamless vision, yet upon closer inspection, the moment of trickery reveals itself, the shift where Mary's severed head begins its deceit, though to the viewer, it remains a singular shot.

In the dim corridors of time, where the past meets the present, the Gothic Novel stands as a paradox, an old-new amalgamation that Ian Watt has called an oxymoron in his exploration, The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This Gothic spirit, like an ancient shadow, has been both scorned and celebrated, accused of shallowness yet revered for its terrible and sublime essence, as Burke once noted. The Castle of Otranto, Horace Walpole's creation, emerged from this twilight, a fusion of the ancient and the modern, carving a path for the Gothic genre, a new voice in the wilderness of literature. Walpole drew from the "old" theatrics and the 'new' mimicry of nature, weaving them into what he proclaimed "A Gothic Story." The genre borrows heavily from the medieval, a nod to the gothic theater, architecture, and traditions of yore. Even then, the word "gothic" was a ghost from many pasts, a descriptor for peoples, styles, epochs, carrying the weight of the archaic and the unsophisticated against the tide of modernity. It is this blend of the theatrical Gothic with the new novel's intimate lens on human psychology that has allowed the Gothic to linger through the ages, becoming both a relic and a revelation to readers far removed from its origins.

Amidst these shadows, the notion of Chivalry rises, like a specter in the Gothic tales. This medieval code, the making of a knight, survives and transforms in The Castle of Otranto, that first Gothic novel. Chivalry held a mirror to the Gothic writers, reflecting the noble knight, brave and honorable, a mirror to what they believed was missing in their world. Through chivalric ideals, the Gothic past is painted in romantic hues, a wistful look forward to Romanticism, an endeavor to mend the present's fractures. Walpole, in the storm of political unrest, looked back at the noble silhouettes of history, despairing at the shadows of his own time. Engulfed in the political turmoil and accusations, his mind turned, perhaps unconsciously, to the lost moral compass and goodness of the Gothic age, absent in his society. This longing is etched in his characters, especially in Frederic, a figure of chivalry, whose reputation precedes him. Frederic steps from the pages, a prince forged in adversity, a tragic figure believed slain by infidels. His image is crafted with chivalric strokes, exaggerated in a way that heralds the Gothic's love for excess, a hallmark to come.

In the bare bones of commerce lies the great machinery of supply chain management, an endless march of goods from the moment a customer dreams of them to their birth in the raw and unformed. It was in the early days of 1982 when a man named Keith Oliver, a consultant, named this stream of processes. He spoke of it as one might speak of a river, a flow of planning and executing and controlling the journey that goods must take, all to sate the needs of the waiting customer. Six are the pillars on which this chain rests: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers, like ancient alchemists, wield these elements to craft a service that meets the restless demands of those they serve.

Production, the first note in this symphony of commerce, stands as the bedrock of the supply chain. It is here that the questions of when and why and where and how ring out, echoing in the minds of those who must decide. The market, a fickle beast, whispers its demands, and the managers listen with intent, deciphering the wants of the masses. With their ears to this ground, they set about determining what must be made, and in what numbers. The place of creation is chosen with care, a factory or plant that promises both volume and quality, all in the pursuit of the customer’s satisfaction. Once the ground is laid, the managers turn their eyes to the scheduling of tasks and the upkeep of the machines that will bring their plans to life. In this meticulous dance, every step is crucial, for a misstep could cost dearly in time and gold. I have seen the inner workings of places like Wal-Mart and Target, where even the smallest detail is mapped, from the color of an employee’s shirt to the route a truck must take. Such plans are the lifeblood of a company, ensuring a smooth course free of confusion and discord.

The second pillar, supply, stands as a testament to the art of decision-making. Here, the strategic minds ponder the core strengths of their facilities, choosing partnerships for outsourcing that will bolster these strengths. In this complex web, a single product may owe its existence to many hands, each division a world unto itself with its own tools and craftsmen. The manager stands as a conductor, deciding which division will play which part, or whether another company should join the orchestra. The heart of this decision is velocity, the power to deliver speed and quality while keeping costs low, a feat much sought after in the halls of business.

In the shadowed corridors of the Victorian age, where the light plays tricks on the eyes and the echo of footsteps is swallowed by the darkness, there are novels that step away from the gilded halls of aristocracy to wander in the terrain of the unknown. Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, they are called. Each a vessel of mystery and the uncanny, diverging from the well-trodden path, their characters emerging from the shadows with motives laid bare by the fires of the bizarre.

The words came at him like a storm, a cacophony of voices and sounds that smothered the air around him. Between Sikes and Crackit he walked, their quarrel ringing in his ears, his own voice mingling with theirs in the fog of his mind. And then, the crack of gunfire, and the world erupted in chaos, a whirl of cries and lights that seared his vision as a phantom hand pulled him away. Amidst this tempest, a dull ache gnawed at him, relentless and unforgiving. (Dickens, 220)

In such tales, the dream is a doorway, a passageway where reality bends and the soul's torment is laid out in stark relief. In Oliver’s world, dreams are a revelation of his inner turmoil, a canvas painted with the colors of his suffering and his awakening to the world’s cruel truths. Chapter 28 finds him immersed in the memory of gunfire, caught in a dream's embrace, seeking refuge yet finding none. The scene unfolds with a sense of helplessness, the grip of fate tight and unyielding. The specters of Sikes and Crackit haunt him, specters born of fear and powerlessness. He is swept away by forces unseen, his senses dulled, pain and dread entwined. Here lies the heart of Oliver’s struggle: the absence of agency, the chains of destiny that bind him, rendering him a passive witness to his own life's unraveling. The specter of Fagin looms large, a shadow cast over Oliver's spirit, whispering resignation into his ear, sapping the will to resist. For in these moments, the boy's struggle is not just with the world, but with the creeping despair that seeks to claim him.

The hours crept by - a day passed, if it could be called day at all, swallowed by the night that followed. Night stretched on, a silent eternity, yet fleeting in its passing, a passage through the void, the minutes fleeing like shadows from the light.

A few years past, I found myself in the halls of a school, an after-hours sanctuary for young minds, lending what aid I could to children finding their way through the murk of learning. My charge was to guide them, these small seekers, in subjects that gave them pause. My own strength lay in the words and the stories they told. Among them was a boy called Adrian, small of stature, perhaps third or fourth grade, facing a peculiar struggle with the written word. Some letters he grasped with ease, others slipped through his understanding like sand through fingers. It puzzled me, for he spoke the language with flawless clarity, though his heritage was Latino. We wrestled with the words until one day his mother came, speaking only in her native tongue, and the truth struck me with the force of revelation. The boy knew the words, but not the symbols of the language they formed. In that moment, a knowledge settled in me, and I could only hope it helped him find his way.

This tale I share not for its own sake but to lay bare the silent walls that rise in our schools, here in this sun-baked land of California. A barrier not of bricks but of tongues. It is a truth hidden in plain sight, that a child may speak the language and yet be a stranger to its written form. The question we must ask is not if this wall exists, for it surely does, but how we might breach it. For Adrian, a path lay in the letters and sounds that eluded him. Yet for others, those who know not the language of this land, the answer is not so simple. There is no solitary cure. The dual language, the immersion in the mainstream, the private guides, the classes of English as a second tongue—none alone will tear down this wall. It is in their union that hope lies.

To take the dual language path is to open doors not only for those whose first words were in the songs of Spanish but for all children. Such programs have shown their worth, their students rising above their peers. Yet fear shadows their implementation, whispers that they waste what cannot be squandered, that the many reap no reward. But these fears are unfounded. Were we to embrace such learning as common practice, all would find enrichment. The question remains, how? Must every teacher speak in two tongues? No, such a demand would be folly. Yet there is no reason we cannot place among them those who do, as aides or tutors, guides fluent in the languages of many.

Since those first glimmers of awareness, the notion has been seeded in us that something larger, ineffable, stands beyond the edge of our understanding. Some are led to sit in pews and listen for whispers of the divine, while others search within, grasping at the shadows of their own souls. Many cling to the faith of their forebears, worn paths trodden by countless feet before them. And yet, there are those who turn their backs on such teachings, declaring their own small world the measure of all things. We may take up one creed only to cast it aside for another, as if the truth were a garment that could be changed with the seasons. Whatever road we walk, we strive to carve out a niche for ourselves, seeking the flicker of light that promises to guide us from the depths of night into the warmth of day.

A cardinal, my father murmured, when I questioned him about his favored bird. We sat upon the porch, the rain drumming a relentless rhythm atop the tin roof, each of us with a cigarette between our fingers. The gutters spewed torrents, drowning the greenery that bordered the porch's edge. His gaze was lost in the rain, a look that seemed to drift between the past and some uncharted horizon. Over the months, he'd dwindled, his clothes hanging loose as though they belonged to another, his hair thinned like a memory fading. He kept his eyes on the rain, as if meeting mine would somehow anchor his spirit. I felt the silence between us, a chasm I dared not cross, for to speak of departure would make it so. I reached for him, drew closer, and together we watched the rain fall in the waning light of June.

He slipped away in December, five days past my twenty-second year. The treatments had bought him time, though what worth was time when pain was its currency, I could not fathom. What deity, I wondered in the lonely dark, would weave such a tapestry of suffering? I found no solace in prayers spent on deaf ears, convinced that if God ever listened, He'd long since turned away.

I could not bear witness to that final breath, the extinguishing of the life that had given me mine. I refused to see him as he waned, preferring the echoes of his laughter to the silence of his end. I knew him better than the others did, knew he would not want me there, watching as he drifted into the unknown. I folded myself into my bed and let the world pass by, waiting for the inevitable.

But no call ever came.

In the shadowed expanse of history, John Taylor of Caroline stood as a figure carved from the very soil he tended. An advocate for Republicanism, his roots were deep in the land, an agriculturalist by nature and a man for whom the earth was both a canvas and a creed. His brief sojourn into the realm of politics did not temper his voice, one of outspoken fervor for the freedom of the individual and the restraint of government. His heart beat for the agrarian life, a rhythm that guided his every thought on sovereignty, the Constitution, and the courts that ruled the land.

Taylor saw this young nation, the United States, as a blank slate, untouched by the ancient traditions that bound older lands. Here was a chance to craft an ideal, to birth a system where self-governance could flourish. He held fast to the notion that the rights of man were natural and intertwined, each reliant on the other. Deny one, and the whole would crumble, their worth diminished. Thus, these rights must lie beyond the grasp of government. In the state of nature, he said, it was the strong and the cunning who thrived, but civilization demanded a different order.

To forge this dream, Taylor knew a government must reckon with the dual nature of man, both virtuous and vile. He spoke of a dual morality, where every virtue and vice of governance was but a reflection of humanity itself. Good governance, Taylor declared, safeguarded private property, nurtured the land, and spurned the greedy clutches of capitalism. Such a government, built on principles true and just, would stand steady, even as those who led it succumbed to greed and self-interest. For Taylor, self-interest was the engine of man, only darkened when it bred societies that thrived on the suffering of others. A vigilant government was needed to chain man's inherent evil, ever watchful to exclude the bad.

In the company of his fellow Republicans, Taylor called for a strict reading of the Constitution, a document that, to him, should bind the Federal government in chains of explicit limits. He saw the sprawl of Federal power as a costly path to despotism. Yet he warned against a simple literalism, for without the spirit of the Founders' intentions, such readings could twist to corruption. To Taylor, the Declaration of Independence was the true heart of the nation, for it spoke of sovereign states bound together, not as one monolith, but as a gathering of equals.

He stood there, gaze fixed downward, seeing but not seeing, his mind a void that absorbed the view without judgment or understanding. The practiced eye of a man who had long since learned to separate the sight from the meaning, a mind that cataloged what it saw but refused to know it, thoughts slipping like whispers through the dark, as if they were not thoughts at all but a mere murmuring of experience washing over him with the ease of a brook over stones.

Once upon a time, in a moment of whim, he had taken the advice of an artist friend and bought a book, The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. A book meant to teach one the art of seeing, of understanding the world through the tip of a pencil, through the lens of line and form. It spoke of frames, of ways to distill the chaos of the world—a bowl of fruit in the cluttered sprawl of a kitchen—into something simple, something graspable, a bowl on a table in a realm of its own.

Yet now, as he stood over the bowl before him, he found no such frame to enclose his sight. There was only the vastness of his awe, a vision too full to be contained. The masters had their colors—Picasso his blues, Monet his greens, those artists of old basking in their prismatic glory. But here, if there was to be any art to his vision, it was the art of brown. This was the canvas spread before him, the genesis of his own peculiar masterpiece.

His fingers settled upon the tool of his creation, muscles tensing and releasing as his hand moved through the air, the will of his mind finding shape in action. Water swirled beneath him, a dance of clarity and calm, carrying with it the fragments of what had been. Again his hand struck, more frantic now, commanding the handle with insistence. But still the stubborn brown form clung to the bottom of the porcelain, unmoved, defiant.

He stood, mop in hand, feet planted firm, the tie at his throat a strangling knot of green. A slight frown creased his brow as he regarded the insolent mass left behind by some nameless soul—a message in waste for the weary keepers of the Rite Aid restrooms. A few more flushes, a few more moments of silent contemplation, then his hand reached for the paper on the wall, winding it round and round until his hand was swathed like some ancient embalmed thing. He straightened, then bent low, his hand descending into the bowl with the careful grace of a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving feast.

The young ones are dying out there on the roads, a grim tally kept by fate and folly. This confluence of hazard, this grim conjoining of statistics, finds its root in the unready minds of the youngest among us. The National Institutes of Health tells a tale of brains not yet ripened for the perils of the road. Inexperience, too, sits heavy at the heart of this dark matter. It is this lack of knowing that leads them astray, to more deaths, to the rolling of vehicles, to the speed that sings of oblivion, to roadsides that catch them unawares.

They fare worse when traveling in packs, these youths, for they are wont to gather and ride, heedless of the danger. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center has mapped the correlation between the age of those who sit beside them and the wreckage left in their wake.

California and other lands have sought to mend this with temporary measures, provisional licenses that bind the hours of their travels and put a stop to the bearing of fellow minors as passengers.

Yet these provisional licenses are but a finger in the dam. The root lies deeper, for by all measures, these young souls are not yet fit to shoulder the burdens of the open road. Marvin Zuckerman, a student of the mind, speaks of eighteen as still too tender an age for such liberty. USA Today bears witness to his findings, the yearning of those not yet reached the age of nineteen, to court risk for the thrill it brings. It stands to reason that patience might temper this seeking, that time might dull the edge of their recklessness.

Should we continue to hand the keys to the young, we shall see the grim harvest continue, the toll rising to heights yet unimagined. Come 2010, the offspring of the Baby Boomers will flood these roads, a legion of new drivers eager to test their mettle.

The crafting of laws to address this is a simple enough matter. Schools might still lay the groundwork with their teachings, yet none under eighteen should know the power that lies beneath their feet. A provisional permit might yet precede the granting of full license, demanding a measure of training that echoes the standards of states such as California, where six hours behind the wheel and fifty in practice are the norm.

For the numbers that haunt us come from every corner of the land, and a single, unified decree could stand as a bulwark against this tide. What I propose is no new thing, but it is a thing that must be done.

In the dim corridors of human understanding, there lies a disorder called Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD. It is a shadowy realm where the brain struggles to sift through the sounds that life throws its way. This disorder, as defined by the American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, concerns itself with the central nervous system's ability to process auditory information, a process that is both delicate and mysterious. For those who wander this path, the hearing is not the issue. They hear as others do, yet the mind falters, unable to untangle the threads of sound from the tapestry of existence.

The whispers of CAPD trace back to the mid-twentieth century, to a time when it was but a fledgling thought, a disorder known then as auditory imperception. It was the Italians, Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari, who began to unravel its secrets, crafting tests in the year of 1954. By 1961, Kimura had stepped into the fray, introducing methods to probe the dichotic nature of perception, revealing the complex physiology beneath. A gathering of minds in 1977 stirred the air with new questions, new paths to tread.

CAPD wears many faces. Those it touches may find themselves adrift in space, unable to pinpoint a sound's origin or distinguish one sound from a chorus of noise. Patterns slip through their fingers, the subtle shifts in speech lost to them like whispers in the wind. Sounds can clash, one blotting out the next, leaving them without the clarity they seek. The sequence of sound eludes them, a puzzle unsolved, a story untold.

To diagnose this elusive disorder, one must embark on a journey of observation and testing. Audiologists and psychologists, with their tools and measures, seek to peel back the layers of auditory behavior, to understand how the patient responds to the world of sound. Yet, the road remains uncertain. No single test shines a light on CAPD's depths, and its origins are shrouded in mystery. Tests, both simple and complex, ask the patient to separate the cacophony, to find meaning in a series of spoken words or numbers. More intricate examinations delve into the ear's acoustics, measuring the echoes of sound within.

And so, the understanding of CAPD continues, a flickering light in the vast darkness of the human mind.

In the pursuit of a life in social work, I find myself drawn toward the path that leads to the Division of Family and Children Services. A path that promises the chance to stand sentinel for those children cast into the shadows of abuse and neglect. A place where troubled families seek refuge and understanding. It is here I aim to lay down the values I hold dear: service to others, respect for every soul, an ethical compass unwavering, a commitment to mend the fractured bonds between people, and an ongoing quest to refine my own professional competence. These are not mere tenets of social work; they are the cornerstone of my own existence.

The urge to help others has been a constant whisper in my heart, even as the path forward lay obscured by uncertainty. Through the corridors of high school and the long halls of college, I witnessed souls grappling with their own ghosts, some fleeing in denial, others resorting to means that offered no peace. It was these encounters that nudged me toward a Bachelor's in Psychology. Yet, upon the completion of my studies at Piedmont College in the year 2009, the road ahead remained a mystery. That summer, a friend led me to a trembling boy of sixteen, perched on her couch, seeking refuge from the storm that was his parents. The next day, he called upon the law to intervene. I followed the call to his home, a silent observer with a newly minted degree in Psychology. The officers, bound by the limits of the law, turned to me. I spoke with the parents, their words a tapestry of excuses painting their son's actions as mere manipulation. This encounter, fraught with the tension of 'simple' disputes, set me on the course toward social work, a calling to aid those ensnared in familial strife.

Social justice stands as another pillar in the field of social work. In our society, we exalt the individual and lament those who slip through our grasp. Yet, this notion of the individual often bows to antiquated traditions rather than true singularity. If society mourns the lost, why then do we strive for sameness? I walk this earth as my own being, unshackled by the chains of conformity. In my time at high school and college, I opposed injustice with every fiber of my being: my hair a canvas of unnatural hues, my attire a reflection of self, my ears adorned beyond convention, my voice loud in the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), my stand firm against racism and discrimination wherever they dared to show their face. I believe in the fight for social justice and vow to continue my protest against its absence.

And so, with each step forward, I carry these truths with me, a testament to the path I aspire to walk, a life dedicated to the service of others, to justice, and to the betterment of the world around me.

The paper you hold is a discourse on the models that bind insomnia to the biological and the sociocultural realms. In the biological sphere, the threads of genetics and the medical weave hold their sway. The sociocultural, in its turn, casts its eye upon the bonds of environment, peering into the depths of race, of ethnicity, of the very fabric of society itself. This review, it dares to uncover, to lay bare the models, to dissect the very heart of the research that lends them voice. In the findings, strengths are revealed, weaknesses too, each one unmasked in the cold light of critique.

A disorder of sleep, it is said, can be known by its kin: a primary disorder, a shadow cast by another mental malady, or yet another tied to the body or the bane of substances. Dyssomnias and Parasomnias claim their place in this pantheon. Dyssomnias—Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, those that warp the breath in sleep, the rhythms of the circadian, and those that stand unnamed. Insomnia, it holds sleep at bay, while Hypersomnia battles to keep the eye unshuttered, both for the span of a month. Narcolepsy, the thief of wakefulness, brings cataplexy and the dream that comes unbidden. The Parasomnias, they walk in the night, bringing nightmares, terrors, movements of sleepwalking, and more that elude the tongue’s grasp. The disorders they link to the mind's troubles, Axis I and Axis II, they too are part of this tale. And so this review draws its focus on insomnia, and the primary disorders of sleep, through the lens of biology and socioculture.

The biological model, it speaks of genes, of inheritance, of the body's own tale in the disorder of sleep. The neurons, the orexin they bear, lie in the hypothalamus, guardians of the cycle of sleep and waking. The study, it took mice as its muse, and found phenotypic GABAB receptors on those neurons of orexin, bearers of the sleep and wake states. The GABAA receptor, when roused, it calls forth sleep. If its fire is quenched, anxiety flees, and sleep is welcomed. The GABAB agonist, baclofen, it lengthened the sleep of the mice (Matsuki et al., 2009). From this, a tale is spun that the mice may yet tell of human sleep. Here is seen the intertwining of genes and the world without, in the GABAB receptor of the human kind. A flaw in this receptor’s tale, and sleep may be lost without the aid of medicine. The sociocultural thread, it whispers of inheritance, of phenotypes guiding sleep, and the twisted tale of a receptor marred. It speaks of the shadows cast upon life, upon learning, upon labor, upon the endless tasks of the day when focus is adrift.

He'd been a student there at University Park for what seemed like the turn of two and a half years, or perhaps four and a half semesters if one reckoned by the calendar of the school. For many who roamed those grounds, himself among them, the very act of moving from place to place was a burden. In that first year they'd placed him in an East Halls dormitory, a place far flung as if it sought to escape the bounds of the campus altogether, save for the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center beyond. The journey from his abode in Stuart Hall to the distant halls of learning at Willard, which lay nearer the heart of the grounds, could consume a good twenty-five minutes by foot. And that on a day when the skies did not conspire against him, as they so often did in State College. An older alum, not many seasons ahead of him, had spoken of a time when those dorms were cut off by vast stretches of barren land. Now that space had been claimed, filled with fields of sport, towering edifices like the new Creamery, and buildings for health, and all circled by apartments like sentinels. As the campus swelled, the struggle to navigate it grew ever more profound. What remedy for this ailment of movement? A simple thing it seemed, the bicycle. Yet the bicycle alone was no panacea. It required the will of students to ride and a campus shaped to their needs.

He'd spoken with a friend who had taken up bicycling once more after some years' neglect. The friend mused aloud, baffled by his own abandonment of such a noble steed. "Bikes are great," he'd said. "For a while, it wasn't the fashion to ride, but it's the sole way to traverse this place." For the body it was a boon, and for travel, unmatched in its efficiency. A simple bowl of oatmeal and some sweat of the brow and a man could cover thirty miles or more. Like many drawn from the dormitories, he now dwelled off campus, no nearer the center than some halls of residence. This year, he'd made the wise choice to purchase a bicycle. Each day brought him to Thomas building, an easy twenty-five-minute walk if he let his legs decide the pace. Yet with the bicycle, he could cut that journey to five if he pushed the pedals hard. But there was Pollock Road, the most direct path, and not always an easy passage, be it on a bike or on foot. Walking had its own merits, true, but time was a luxury he could not afford. Without that bicycle, he'd be bound to walk, and that daily trek would steal another thirty to forty minutes from his hours. Over a week, he'd be losing more than two and a half hours. And more yet if he counted the other journeys to classes and appointments and such. Time he could ill spare in the days allotted to him.

In the somber landscape of Brave New World, Aldous Huxley crafts a vision where the specter of technology looms large, its great shadow cast by the capitalist machinations that bind it. Here lies a world where the community smothers the individual, and the pursuit of fleeting happiness is a creed whispered into the ear from birth. A populace molded into pawns, their lives governed by the unseen hand of the World Controller, their thoughts tethered to a single dogma. Through the lens of Marxist theism, one might discern Huxley’s deep-seated wariness of these burgeoning constructs. Terms born of Marxism—homogeny, reification—dance through the narrative, underscoring Huxley’s critique of the economic tides of his era.

The satire of capitalism unfurls in the guise of false consciousness, a Marxist thesis that cloaks the masses from understanding their true standing among the economic strata. They are ensnared by the lure of personal gain, their sight blinded by the ideological chains that bind the proletariat and laborers, mirrored in the conditioning suffered by the denizens of Huxley’s world. The Deltas, the Gammas, each class stripped of will, their minds reshaped by hypnopædia to consume, to spend, to revel in excess as ordained by the World Controller. The grip of hegemony encircles them, a specter of domination wherein the lower classes remain oblivious to their own subjugation, buying into an ideology that props up the edifice of capitalism and consumerism. The Alphas and Betas, birthed with the awareness of their bondage, remain inert, save for the few like Bernard who dare to question. The dance of social classes, a tapestry of oppression under the capitalist yoke, unfolds with stark clarity.

In this world, the ties that bind disparate souls unravel, the novel refusing to grant its characters the nuance of depth. Huxley’s hand perhaps suggesting that the ascent of technology and capitalism strips man of his soul and voice. Love is a phantom, and emotion a shadow—interactions rendered shallow, as men speak of women in terms of their pneumatic allure, and women recount their liaisons with unabashed candor. The complacency of each class in their societal rung echoes the economic tendrils of capitalism. Their unyielding allegiance to their role within the hive mind mirrors Marxist insights into the proletariat, convinced of their supremacy so long as they consume, adhere, and march in step with their brethren.

It was near four years past when I took a course in Islam at CBC. A class filled with voices rising and falling over a single question that seemed to stretch beyond the walls of the room: Is Islam a hostile religion? Such a question now, in these days, seems more pressing than ever. From the shadows of 9/11, I have watched the media's gaze shift. Once, it looked upon Islam with fear, with suspicion, but now it seems to have swung to a strange patience, a tolerance not easily understood. Hard to imagine in those days of 2001 that a man like Barack Obama, bearing a name tethered to a Muslim lineage, could stride into the arena of presidential ambition.

The Prophet's life, in its telling, intrigued me. A biography that seemed to run against the grain of what I had come to know of Muhammad. I had thought him a man who bent others to his will, who took tribes and made them kneel to the creed of Islam. Yet, in those pages, he was cast anew, a martyr misunderstood, humbling himself before others, the truth of his teachings drawing the people to him one by one.

There are lines drawn between the stories of Jesus and the so-called miracles of Muhammad that are difficult to ignore. In the tale where he multiplied mutton and milk until forty men had eaten their fill, I see an attempt to paint him as a prophet who walked in truth and miracles, needing nothing more to prove his worth. It feels a theft, a shadow cast over the light of Jesus Christ, an attempt to weave the life of one into the fabric of another's legend.

The biography is threaded with tales that speak of conversions, of witnesses coming to the truth of their own accord. Yet these stories seem spun from hearsay, tales told by those who heard from another and another still. It is a thing that sits uneasily with me, for while it seeks to stand as proof, it leaves a shadow of doubt, a whisper of suspicion.

What gnaws at me most is the way they lift Muhammad, setting him upon a pedestal as a man of divine grace, humble and wise. Yet history casts another light, one that tells of a rise to power that speaks little of gentleness. I wonder if those who follow him today know this history that lies beneath the surface of his story.

In the twilight of beliefs where the gospels were first whispered, the teachings of Jesus lay like stones in a streambed, unmoved and unheeded as the waters of Christian thought rushed past in their ceaseless journey. With the passage of time, the river of faith meandered, leaving behind the roots that anchored its beginning. Through the ages, you can see the world of Christianity diverging from its primal path, like travelers who have lost their way. Yet now, in the looming present, there is a rumbling beneath the earth, a stirring of the spirit that speaks of return. The old ways hold firm like ancient oaks in a restless forest, but the winds of change are strong, and they whisper of a coming day when history shall turn upon itself. 

In the years ahead, Christians will find themselves drawn to the echoes of their faith's origins, yearning to strip away the layers of doctrine that have gathered like dust upon an ancient artifact. This slow revelation will be as inexorable as the tide, a movement that pares back the centuries until only the essence of Jesus’ message remains, unmarred by the hands of time. Across the lands of America and Europe, the faithful will rise like shadows at dawn, seeking a purer communion. The church will stand as a bastion, guiding the faithful back along the path to where it all began. With every step retraced, the myriad voices of Christendom will meld into a single chorus, the discord of division fading into a harmony of belief.

History is a wheel that turns upon itself. Once, Christians were hunted and scorned by Rome, yet Rome became the heart of their faith. The land of freedom bore the scars of bondage, only to see those once shackled rise to lead it. In the days to come, this great wheel will turn again, drawing the threads of Christian faith back to their source, unraveling the tapestry of differences woven through the ages. This unraveling will not be of violence but of understanding, as the words of Jesus are read not as stone-carved edicts but as the poetry of metaphor. 

Look back far enough, and you find the roots entwined deep in Judaism, that ancient soil from which the sapling of Christianity grew. The Romans came, and the Jewish people split like a tree into branches, each reaching toward the sky in its own way—Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the quiet multitude. These divisions were the seeds of what would become, yet from them all grew the solitary figure of Jesus, whose message would one day call the faithful back to the beginning, where the river first began its course.

In the shadowed labyrinth of Packingtown, where the sky itself seemed to be a canvas for the soot and ash of ambition, there lay the stark truth of mankind's naked avarice. The Jungle, Sinclair's bitter ode to the industrial age, unveils the primal greed that festers within the human soul. A world where men look only to their own gain, their eyes cold to the plight of those trampled beneath their relentless ascent. Here the factory owners, lords of smoke and metal, wrought their empire with a callous disregard for the lives consumed in their furnace of progress. The great chimneys rose like obelisks, their plumes of smoke a testament to the sacrifice of the earth and its creatures, a sacrifice unheeded by those who reaped its spoils.

The workers, mere cogs in the great machine, were held in thrall to a merciless whim. For a dollar, they were bound, their worth measured in coin and not in flesh. "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds," Sinclair writes, a world where loyalty is a forgotten relic and decency a ghost. They toiled under a sunless sky, the hours long, the reward scant, and at the end of the day, the axe could fall without warning, casting them adrift into the night. In this grim epoch, the law was a specter, the worker's guardian absent, and the factories a wilderness where only the strong or the cunning survived.

Yet, beyond the din and clamor, there was a deeper silence, a silence of souls worn thin by the grindstone of survival. The unions, a false beacon, often preyed upon the very men they claimed to shield, their coffers filled from the pockets of the poor. The men of Packingtown were bound by chains unseen, their lives a cycle of endless toil, their cries swallowed by the great maw of industry. "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign," Sinclair laments, "hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers." In this wasteland, morality withered, and the human spirit lay shackled, as inevitable and pervasive as the very smoke that blotted out the sun.

In the dim corridors of literature's past, where the echoes of great minds linger, Edgar Allan Poe whispered of a land beyond the veil of dreams. "Dream-Land," he called it, a poem he held close to his heart. In its verses, the name "Thulé" surfaces, a name that Virgil once uttered, conjuring visions of an island far north of Britain, a place where the world as known faded into the unknown. Virgil's mention was sure, yet Poe's fascination with the works of German minds was a thread that wove through his own creations.

There, in the shadows of his words, lay a connection to Goethe, a titan of German letters. Karl J. Arndt, in his musings upon Poe's "Politian" and Goethe's "Mignon," saw the mirrored lines and drew a line from one to the other, whispering of imitation. Goethe, whose name graced the pages of the Oxford Companion to English Literature, stood as a colossus, his "Faust" a gem of poetic drama, unfolding in two acts—the first in 1808, the second marking the twilight of his life in 1832. Within this epic tale, nestled like a secret, was a poem of a king named Thule.

A king who clutched a goblet, a gift from his departed queen, and in his grief, drank deep from its depths. In his sorrow, he cast the goblet into the sea and, with eyes closed to the world, followed it into the eternal night. The king's tale, a mirror darkly held to Poe's own struggles and losses, perhaps echoed in the land of dreams Poe traversed. Faust's tale found a new voice in H. P. Grattan's romantic drama in 1842, a whisper away from Poe's "The Pit and the Pendulum," where "ultima Thule" found its place.

In Poe's collected words, Thule emerged twice, a haunting refrain. In "Dream-Land," it framed the poem, a land of shadows where dead friends walked and colors fled. It mirrored Goethe's king, bereft of his queen, lost in a world without light or life. The two, Poe's vision and Goethe's lament, walked side by side, a dialogue across the pages of time.

Goethe, a figure Poe would have known, if only for the echoes of Tennyson's admiration. When Poe spoke of Tennyson, the respect for Goethe was an unspoken bond. The world of letters knew Goethe's works, their reproductions spreading like wildfire, and Poe, ever the seeker, would have found them in the dim light of his study, the ink still fresh upon the page.

In the dim corridors of law and consequence, the question arises. In the state of California, where the sun bakes the land and the law intertwines justice with the unpredictable hand of fate, can a soul wounded in body and spirit from a fall on an errant spill of applesauce in a grocery's aisle seek retribution beyond mere compensation? Can they claim the punitive with whispers of malice against the one who turned a blind eye twice to the hazard that lay there unheeded, left alone for the half-hour it takes to finish a meal?

The judge, a figure carved of patience and deliberation, would be hesitant to sweep aside Jennifer Palmer’s plea for punitive recompense. To cast her claim in the iron of justice, she must lay bare the evidence that the overseer's deeds were done not in ignorance but in willful defiance of the harm that lay just beneath the surface, like a serpent in the grass. She must paint his actions in hues of darkness, despicable in their neglect. Palmer can stand before them and weave her tale, that the keeper of the store should have known the peril of leaving a spill untended, for in the months before, others had fallen victim to the same fate, their stories not unlike hers. Yet he turned away, his back to their plight. Her tale of his despicable disregard, though less forceful, finds its strength in the history of six others who had fallen before her, in that same year of trials, and still he chose inaction.

The clock marks the day, October 13, 2009, at the hour of five in the evening. Rich Wayne, a humble worker of D&D Markets, bore witness to the spill and sought his superior, Paul Martin, who was then at table, breaking bread. Martin, wrapped in the cloak of indifference, dismissed the concern with words that echoed his disregard, speaking of his meal and the lack of time for the troubles of patrons. A quarter of an hour passed, and another voice, Mary J. Haddigan, spoke the same warning. Yet Martin, steadfast in his negligence, echoed his prior dismissal. As the half-hour turned its course, Palmer found herself lost in the applesauce, her back caught in the gravity of neglect. Five others before her had met similar fates in that year at D&D's door. Now she seeks justice, both to mend her body and to punish the careless hand.

In the realm of California's statutes, one may claim punitive damages when a breach arises not from the bonds of contract but from a more sinister place, where oppression, fraud, or malice dwell. The law, etched in the annals of time, speaks of malice as a deed done with intent to harm. Absent such intent, it must be a deed despicable, wrought with a conscious disregard for the rights or safety of others. The courts, bastions of reason, have named actions malicious when done with a knowing shrug at the danger they pose, when the actor saw the storm coming and chose to stand in its path. Such is the measure of malice in the eyes of the law.

She'd always been searching for something in the quiet hours of her life. A yearning that lingered like a shadow since she was fourteen, just stepping into the turbulent world of adolescence. Three years had passed and still the ache remained, a constant whisper in the back of her mind. She reckoned it was not a thing she sought but a person, yet no boy caught her interest. They courted her in their clumsy, adolescent way, but she found no appeal in their fumbling attempts. She puzzled over this strange absence of desire, pondering what made her different from the other girls. The years had spun out possibilities, none of which satisfied her quiet inquiries. So she moved through life, a question unanswered.

Home was a sanctuary of peace. Her parents, quiet souls who rarely raised their voices in anger, found little to dispute with their daughter. Their only tiffs arose from her declarations of independence, her insistence on her own path. Hers was a spirit lively and bright, a counterpoint to their calm demeanor, endearing her to those who crossed her path. 

But today the peace was shattered. As she moved through the house, seeking some spark of inspiration, a cry pierced the air. Her mother's voice, once melodic, now sharp with pain. Fear gripped her as she raced to the kitchen. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay crumpled on the floor, pain drawing short breaths from her lips. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words came squeezed and hurried, the anguish clear. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother gestured weakly, and the daughter, grateful for her strength, hoisted her up. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

The hospital loomed, a place of antiseptic smells and quiet dread. But her mind was fixed on her mother, blocking out the rest. She bore her inside, calling out for aid. Faces gathered, concern etched in their lines. A bed appeared and they laid her mother upon it, wheeling her away for immediate care, while the daughter was left to worry alone.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool, reaching for a vase on the highest shelf, and now the daughter sat with her thoughts, waiting in the sterile quiet.

In the long corridors of human inquiry, one study set its gaze upon the Mediterranean Diet, a regimen born of sunlit groves and blue waters, where olive groves whisper secrets to the sea. The scholars sought to find if this diet, in its alternate form, with its score that marked adherence, could indeed ward off the specter of chronic heart disease and the silent approach of stroke. This aMed diet, as they named it, diverged from the traditional path, placing greater faith in the bounty of plants, the quiet strength of plant proteins, the soft whisper of monounsaturated fats over the harsh tones of their saturated kin, and the gifts of the ocean. It held back from the excesses of flesh and fat and allowed for the gentle tide of alcohol in moderation.

The annals of past studies spoke of the Med diet’s power to stave off the finality of cardiovascular demise, and an intervention proclaimed its superiority over the low-fat path, in guiding the weight-laden to lighter shores and taming the unruly tides of cholesterol. Yet, the shadow of stroke had not been their focus.

The study wound its way through the lives of 74,886 women, aged and unscarred by the diseases they sought to avoid, nurses all, who dwelled across eleven states of this vast land. Six times, from the year 1984 to 2004, they turned in their accounts of what they consumed, each morsel and sip etched into the record. The diligence of these women was near unwavering, with more than ninety-five percent remaining faithful to the study’s call across two decades. The truth of their reports was tested against the hard facts of medical records and the finality of death certificates, carving out a path of certainty in a world of probabilities.

They watched these women, calculated their body’s measure, their habits of smoke and aspirin, of vitamins and hormones, and from 1986, their leisure pursuits. They sought to smooth the rough edges of random chance, averaging the diet scores to better reflect the truth of years lived. They adjusted their sights for confounding factors, those tricksters that might lead them astray.

Through the lens of Cox proportional-hazard models, they peered at the ties between diet and disease, separating the fatal from the nonfatal in their quest for clarity. They found that those who embraced the Mediterranean way, with scores that reached the heights of the aMed scale, faced a lesser risk of heart and mind’s betrayal. Across the span of twenty years, the numbers gathered: 2391 incidents of heart's affliction, 1763 strokes, and 1077 deaths of cardiovascular ilk. Those at the pinnacle of the aMed scale bore a risk far diminished, a relative risk of 0.71, compared to those at the scale’s nadir.

Thus, in the twilight of the study, the words were spoken: the Mediterranean way, in its alternate guise, stands as a sentinel against the ravages of heart and stroke.

Hitler alive in Burma, the sign declares. 

Ellen Page, known for her role in Juno, stands solitary on a street corner, her cardboard placard raised aloft, a stark message scrawled in Sharpie. Burma, a land by another name called Myanmar, lies in the grip of a tyrannical junta, its power seized in the coup of 1962. In the year of 2007, the streets bore witness to protests unseen for a decade. Monks in their saffron robes led these uprisings, a revolution named for the hue of peace they wore. The populace soon followed, and though the junta permitted the monks their assembly at first, violence soon reared its head. Monasteries fell to the military's wrath. Foreign journalists were seized, a Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, met his end on the streets, a casualty of presence. Official accounts claim thirteen souls lost, yet Colonel Hla Win, who turned from the army days before, spoke of a toll in thousands, bodies uncounted, unspoken.

Such tales are old as time. A government's iron grip, its need to silence dissent, is a shadow etched across history’s pages. Emperors of Rome named themselves chosen by deities to rule unchallenged. In Japan, emperors claimed divine descent, destined to lead through the making of cell phones and ritual death. The president of our time, George W. Bush, finds counsel in weekly calls with Ted Haggard, a leader of fools under the Republic Party's banner.

The world knows these tales. Tiananmen Square in the June of 1989, where scholars and workers and the young stood against their rulers, and the numbers of the dead lost in the fog of conflicting tales. Rwanda in the 1990s, where Hutu militias with the government's aid wrought genocide upon the Tutsis and moderates alike. And Hitler’s Third Reich, spreading darkness across continents, where Jewish lives were taken in the thousands, an atrocity among the ages.

Such shadows, ever lingering.

In the dim glow of a smoky room where the notes of jazz hung heavy like the wreaths of smoke that curled and twisted about, there sat Duke Ellington at the piano. His fingers, delicate and sure, touched the keys with a subtlety that seemed almost an afterthought amidst the elaborate tapestry of sound he wove with his orchestra. An orchestra shaped by time, by the honing of talent and the forging of a singular vision that was Ellington's. In the compositions laid before him, his presence was a whisper, a shadow. Yet it was as a composer he truly sang, crafting pieces of such richness and complexity that they stood as monuments to the prowess of each band member. He was the architect of a musical landscape where soloists could roam, improvisations unbound, against a backdrop of meticulously orchestrated passages.

Ellington understood the voices of his musicians, each a unique brushstroke on his canvas, and it was this mastery that allowed him to conjure sounds both coherent and original. His compositions were a testament to this understanding, marked by innovation and brilliance that would ripple through the annals of jazz history. The Grove Music dictionary speaks of Ellington’s sound, of Creole Love Call where the voice was not mere words but an instrument, a texture, a color. It was in this piece his genius shone, as he complemented the soloists' style, a thread through the fabric of his career.

The slow, deliberate unfolding of Creole Love Call in twelve bar blues, six choruses, each a story unto itself. The voice and reeds in call and response, the trumpet muted and blue, the clarinet soaring with syncopated piano whispers, the full band echoing, the climactic swirl of reeds and brass, the voice growling, the trombone’s dissonant farewell. Here was Ellington, weaving voice into the very soul of the music.

A year passed and in Hot and Bothered, Ellington’s ear for tone color found its match in tight orchestration, in the dance between “Bubber” Miley’s trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat, a conversation in sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) bore witness to these ideas stretched further, Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton’s trombone muted and melodic, the melody a thread that tied it all together. These were the sounds of Ellington, a legacy in jazz’s long, winding road.

In the silent hours when questions of change whisper in the dark, we find ourselves asking just why creatures shift and mold as they do. What unseen hand guides their becoming? A century has passed since D’Arcy Thompson mused on the mathematic's reach, and yet the mystery holds. Today, new equations seek to unravel the shell's secret. In the realm of Prunum's form, we delve, threading numbers through its ancient spirals, hoping to seize the ghost of change itself. 

With X-rayed eyes, we search the bones of Prunum, seeking the shape's truth. Quantities become keys, unlocking doors to shells that might be or have been, their forms cast in the digital ether of CerioShell. Alongside the hands-on craft of experiment, these spectral shells speak of the great dance of evolution in their stony silence.

Consider the shell: a spiraling journey through time, born from the deep axis of its own becoming. Whorls grow like whispered secrets, each turn a chapter in the tale, bound by the suture’s line. The last whorl, body and breadth, tells of the end's beginning. The spire lifts its apex to the heavens, while below, the base anchors its tale. Through the aperture, life reaches out, touching the world beyond its carapace.

The shell in its manifold faces—apical, basal, apertural, abapertural—each view a new world. To count the whorls is to trace the shell's life from the start, marking the suture's first breath. From that line, quarter by quarter, the tale unfolds.

See the shell not just as structure but as story. A path traced through the ether, the aperture’s journey marked by the passage of days, the growth of an unseen hand. Plotted in space and time, the shell’s tale can be told in numbers. And with those numbers, a new tale begins to form, a mollusk's life rewritten through the lens of math and mind.

The numbers tell a tale of stasis. In Indonesia, the breath of the newborn and the pulse of the infant linger in a place unyielding, unbroken by the sun or the passing of shadows, for the span of a decade. The nation strides toward certain goals, the water and the sanitation, they say, but the mothers and the children, they wait, their dreams unmet, the year of 2015 a forlorn beacon. The reasons are many, tangled like roots beneath the earth, and speak to a need for strength in the system, not the fleeting balm of isolated interventions.

In the realm of birth, there is progress, if it can be called such. A skilled hand at 72 percent of births, though the term skilled is stretched thin, including those who know not the ways of medicine should the fates turn against the mother. Hemorrhage claims them still, the blood a testament to the gap between what is and what should be. The numbers deceive, for the truth remains, a truth that demands more than has been given. The children, too, suffer, with fewer seen by a healer's eye when struck by the scourge of diarrheal disease. The care after birth is a haze, incomplete, a concern that stretches across the archipelago.

The knife that saves, the cesarean, is wielded too rarely, at 4 percent where it should be more. In the city, it is seen more often, but in the fields and the hills, only 2 percent know its edge. A country divided, access a privilege of the city, the wealth, a chasm between those who have and those who have not. The poor walk a harder road to the healer's door, their pockets lighter, the cost a barrier that looms large.

The path forward is a question, a question of how best to mend what is broken. Is it a matter of programs, each a spear aimed at a single target, or should the foundation be strengthened, the whole given the attention it needs? The allure of the program is strong, its goals clear, its results quick as a hawk's strike. But the dangers are there, too, the risks that one focus draws away the lifeblood from others, as has been seen with the call of HIV/AIDS drawing away from family planning. The programs run parallel like streams uncoordinated, leading to a flood of forms and papers that drown what they seek to aid.

These are the choices, the paths before us in the dim light of the present.

In the span of a century, the realm of Popular Music has unfurled like a tapestry of myriad hues and textures, each thread a genre unto itself, so tangled and vast that one might lose themselves in the mere naming of them. And yet, within this labyrinth, the seed of a singular creation has given rise to a multitude of branches, each one a sub-genre reaching out into the dark unknown. Among these, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal stands like a colossus, its form and nature shifting across the years, becoming both a mirror and a shadow of the human soul. It is a genre that speaks in tongues of fury and despair, a cacophony of emotions drawn from the night’s darker palette.

Heavy Metal is a chameleon. Born of a time when the world sought to break from the shackles of convention, it grew in breadth and depth, its roots spreading wide as artists discovered its boundless potential. It became a tree of many branches, each branch a sub-genre, and then those branches bore smaller branches, sub-sub-genres, until the tree was vast and its identity elusive. In this tangled forest of sound, what once was called Heavy Metal is now a question with many answers, a chimera of borrowed themes and borrowed voices.

To understand this beast, one must trace its lineage and delve into the heart of the movement. Metal is more than a genre; it is a force, a movement that sweeps through the world, defined by its darkness. It is a music of excess, where the bass rumbles like distant thunder, where the volume is a tempest, where violence and theatrics are woven into its very fabric. It is a place where musicians wield their instruments with the precision of a surgeon and the fury of a storm. Metal is born of a time when the air was thick with the haze of psychedelic dreams, a time when madness was a muse and otherworldly visions were set to sound. It is a music that speaks of the abyss, a visceral language new to the ears of those accustomed to the light.

From this dark wellspring emerged songs like "Helter Skelter," a harbinger of the metal to come, a dark echo from the Beatles not unlike the shadows thrown by the Rolling Stones. A challenge, a proclamation that they too could summon the weight of the world’s shadows into song. Thus did they etch their mark upon The White Album, a testament made in sound and fury.

Long before the Surrealists set their dreams to canvas, Henri Rousseau crafted his own visions, both in paint and in the quiet longing of his heart. The Dream, a work from 1910, stands as testament to more than the woman who gazes in wonder at a strange land conjured from sleep. It bears the weight of Rousseau's own yearnings, the painter's dream of recognition, of acceptance in the circles of artists and patrons alike. He wrestled with a dilemma as old as art itself: to follow the well-trodden paths of style for the validation of the art world, or to strike out into the wilderness of his own imagination. The Dream captures this struggle, a reflection of his life's pursuit.

To see this painting for what it is, one must know the man behind it. Henri Rousseau was born on a spring day in 1844, in Laval, a place nestled in the northwest of France. His father, a tinsmith and dealer in hardware, found some measure of prosperity, though no such fortune awaited Rousseau in art's world. His journey began without the guiding hand of formal education, and for decades he served as a gabelou, a toll collector, though the name douanier, customs inspector, clung to him mistakenly. Grief visited his life early, with the passing of his first wife, Clémence, and eight of their children, leaving him only his daughter, Julia. In painting, he sought solace, a new beginning amidst a sea of loss. Unlike the painters who cast the peasant in romantic hues, Rousseau painted from the heart of his own world, with dreams and hopes that mirrored those of his peers.

Rousseau's yearning for acceptance is a thread that runs through his life. Unversed in the formalities of art, he came to it late, his work emerging in the shadow of more celebrated contemporaries. Recognition did not come easily or soon. It was only as Matisse began to rise that Rousseau's light flickered brighter. In Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon speaks of their contrast: where Matisse feared the banal, Rousseau sought the familiar, craving the approval of the Artiste Français.

In the end, The Dream is more than a painting; it is the tale of a man's soul laid bare, its colors and forms whispering of the path he chose, the dreams he dared to follow.

In the quiet creeds of thinkers past and present, there lies a tether binding ethics to aesthetics, truth to beauty. As if in the marrow of things a reason abides, waiting for the light. Keats whispered it in the lines of an urn, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty," like a gospel for the earthbound, all they need to know and all they ever will. The knowing we carry is burdened by lessons learned and experiences lived, yet in the realm of ethics and aesthetics, there is a knowing that comes unbidden, unschooled. They speak not in commands but in whispers, tracing the outlines of a world where beauty and morality are not dictated but discerned. Our minds strive to explain the grace of a painting, the righteousness of an act, but fall short of prescribing what makes them so.

In the telling of art or morals, that essence slips through the fingers. Take da Vinci's Mona Lisa, where scholars speak of light and shadow, of time and place, yet these words cannot grasp the heart of her. Ask a man his favorite work and you will hear the telling pause, the something about it that defies the tongue. Art and morals, like stories, live beyond their telling, as O'Connor spoke, for a story holds what a statement leaves wanting. Describe a tale, and you miss what lies beyond, something that cannot be captured in the net of words. Ethics, too, eludes the grasp of speech, as Wittgenstein knew, for it is transcendental, living in the spaces between words. This something, this ineffable quality, it is the power that art and morality wield, the bridge between what is seen and what is felt.

Morality and art, bound as they are, reach us at a depth beyond reason, a noumenal realm Kant named. They touch us in ways clear and yet unexplainable. In literature, the bond deepens, for in its pages dwell the moral fibers that weave through life itself. Like McKean said, literature stands apart, its moral core unyielding, as essential as breath to life. For life is values entwined, and literature calls to us with those values laid bare. It is in the telling of tales that we find ourselves, and in the finding, understand what cannot be spoken.

In the gray dawn of Europe's heart, Germany stands unyielding, a land forged in the crucible of time, its culture a river flowing from the shadowed Alps of München to the distant shores of Kiel, where the Baltic whispers secrets of old world seas. This same current runs through Köln by the Rhine's timeless embrace, through the very core of Germany, until it reaches Dresden's Saxon soul on the banks of the Elbe. A culture so singular, borne from the loam of forgotten tribes and fractured realms.

Germania, the ancient marrow of this nation, holds its name shrouded in the mists of scholarly quarrel. Tacitus, in his chronicles, spoke of a tribe, the Tungrians, who bore this name, their banners flying before the Gauls in battle's din. Caesar, that conqueror of old, first set the word “Germanus” into the annals of his Gallic conquests, borrowing from the Gauls to mark those fierce beyond the Rhine, warring ceaselessly with the tribes he had yet to subdue. The origin, a ghostly thing, whispers of neighbors in the Gaulish tongue, while others claim it springs from the spear, the ger, or the shouts of battle, a garim, echoing through time.

Tacitus himself penned the tale of these people in his "De Origine et situ Germanorum," casting them as unchanged, untouched by the mingling of races, fierce and true in their homeland of storm-ridden skies and unyielding earth. "Who," he wondered, "would forsake the warmth of Asia or Africa for this harsh clime, unless it were their blood's call?"

And so it was, not the Romans who sought Germania's embrace, but their reach extending, seeking the wealth of its soil, sending their legions to test the bounds of empire. But always they returned to their Rome, vast and sprawling, while the tribes of Germania grew, living at the empire's edge, trading their earth's bounty, their warriors marching under Roman standards, their eyes always cast back to the dark forests and the land that bore them. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

In the play Twelfth Night, the use of disguise unfurls a tale of deception that, while beguiling in its utility, demands eventual renunciation lest one loses themselves in the masquerade. Yet, the shedding of such guises brings with it the chill of isolation, a casting out into the wilds of one's own making. Thus, the choice looms: self-preservation or the fragile tendrils of connection that bind us to the world. For some, the revelation of deceit is met with mere bemusement, but others find their pride wounded, the farce a bitter draught they are loath to swallow.

The entanglement of disguise with the reversal of gender roles weaves a web tangled with questions of identity. Why does one cloak themselves in the garb of another gender? Viola stands as a testament to survival, her donning of masculine attire a shield against the unknown perils of foreign shores: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town / Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help / I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). Her ruse holds, yet it casts her adrift from the women who might offer solace, severing her from the sisterhood she might have claimed. Olivia, deceived by appearances, mistakens her for Sebastian and entwines herself in love’s folly: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Meanwhile, Viola grapples with the unspoken pull towards Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times / Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To those who tread the modern path, Twelfth Night offers a lens through which deception lays bare the hidden chambers of the heart. Olivia and Orsino, drawn into Viola’s orbit, must confront desires whispered yet unvoiced. Is Olivia’s affection for Cesario born of the guise of manhood, or does it whisper of a deeper truth? Perhaps it is not so, for Olivia, in Shakespeare’s hands, might simply mirror those who judge by sight alone. Her swift turn of heart from Cesario to Sebastian, and the familial embrace of Viola, signal the transience of her affections: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

In the annals of time where men carved out empires upon the backs of others, the German dominion over foreign lands stands noted for its harshness, a brutality that bore witness in the blood and dust of the Ovaherero and Nama peoples beneath the unyielding sun of German South West Africa. Yet to account for an empire's breadth by a singular stroke is to ignore the variegated tapestry of its existence. The German colonial empire stretched across vast lands, each corner as unique in governance as the very soil it claimed. Within its borders, the efforts to educate were as diverse as the lands themselves. When the British took the reigns of German East Africa, now known as Tanganyika, in the year nineteen hundred and nineteen, they found a people not wanting for knowledge, their minds sharpened by the tutelage of those who came before. Praises were penned for German endeavors in Kamerun and other far-flung reaches where scholars wrote of the day's light cast upon eager minds. Yet South West Africa, the land now called Namibia, stood in stark relief against such tales. There, unlike the far fields of East Africa where schools rose at the hand of the state, the task of imparting knowledge fell to those of the cloth, missionary societies left to their own devices with nary a nod from the powers that be. Yet for the European children, there was no such lack. Resources flowed like a river to their schools, state-backed, well-ordered, and watched over with a keen eye. The echoes of these choices lingered long past the German's departure. Where other lands could boast of learned men, South West Africa remained a land where many had not touched the written word. The reasons for this divergence lie in a tangled web of social, political, and economic threads. This study seeks to unravel those threads, to gaze upon the hearts and minds of settlers and those who ruled from afar. The pages of history are filled with words on German colonial education, penned mostly in German in the early days when the empire still held its sway. These works sought to capture the essence of learning in those distant lands. Later, the English tongue took up the tale, comparing the ways of Germany's scattered territories and delving deep into their secrets. It was Cohen who spoke most clearly on the matter, casting his eye upon the schools of South West Africa and East Africa, laying bare the forces that shaped them. He spoke of the settlers, the many who called South West Africa home, and how their presence shaped that land's pursuit of knowledge. In the reckoning of Germany's holdings, South West Africa stood apart. Its climate, though kinder than some, bore the harshness of the desert. Yet by the year nineteen hundred and thirteen, fifteen thousand souls of European descent had made it their home, a number unmatched save in the more temperate climes of East Africa.

In the annals of time, there stood two nations, the United States of America and Mexico, locked in a dance of rivalry that spanned the breadth of fifty-seven years. From the year of 1836 to the dawn of 1893, a time when the world turned slowly on its axis and men measured their days by the rising and falling of the sun. It was a rivalry marked by blood and fire, by the clash of cultures and the unyielding grip of tradition. The high-water mark of this enmity came with the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, when the United States, hungry for land and power, bore down upon Mexico with the fury of a storm, wresting from its grasp Texas and the American Southwest. In those days, the earth trembled under the weight of armies, and the sky was darkened by the smoke of battles fought and lost. Yet, even as the dust settled, other skirmishes flared, like echoes of a distant thunder, until at last the storm abated, just before the first great war of the world.

In their struggle, these two nations were not alone. For across the vast expanse of the world, many lands have known the bitter taste of rivalry with their neighbors. Nations that share a border often find themselves at odds, their interests clashing like the waves against a rocky shore. The United States and Mexico were no different from countless other rivalries that have arisen between nations bound by geography. David M. Pletcher once observed that only in Mexico and Cuba did there exist long-lasting American diplomatic problems. These lands, so close and yet so far, have always been rivals to the United States, even as other nations in the Americas found a more peaceful accord.

Religion, that old specter, cast a long shadow over their relations. It was a rift as ancient as time itself, for throughout history, nations have been torn asunder by religious discord. Sally Frahm spoke of how, if in the twentieth century Americans stood against fascism and communism, in the centuries before, they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy. It was an ideological struggle, not unlike the cold war that later gripped the world, but here it was not politics that stood in opposition, but the very soul of belief. The distrust grew deep, a legacy of the enmity between the English and the Spanish, inherited like a dark heirloom from their colonial pasts, a barrier to the peace both nations sought.

Diehl and Goerts chronicled the disputes, seventeen in all, marking the years of rivalry like notches on a weathered staff. Most were born of the land itself, of territorial disputes and border raids, of bandits and outlaws who haunted the edges of civilization. These raids, like wolves circling at the edge of the firelight, were a scourge that persisted until both nations, weary of the bloodshed, brought forth their armies to restore order.

But as time wore on, as the sun rose and set upon the land, the rivalry began to wane. Mexico, bound by the chains of circumstance, grew dependent upon the United States in ways substantial and profound. In the twilight of the nineteenth century, American ambitions shifted, from the lust for land to the desire for economic influence, and the fires of rivalry cooled, leaving only the embers of what once had been.

Fifteen years past, I found myself felled by an ailment unknown to me, an affliction that crept in like a thief, leaving me bereft of the life I once knew. I was a nurse then, drawn to its call by a deep and abiding need for the safety that eluded my younger years. They would say, as if reciting a sacred verse, "You'll always find work; folks will always fall ill." And so, though my heart leaned toward the pursuit of science or the written word—both, if fate allowed—I took up nursing.

Yet there I was, forty-six, unaccompanied, with nary a coin to my name and no strength left to labor. To this day, I remain shackled by disability, the years of Social Security dwindling my possessions to naught. I endure, but each day is a siege upon my spirit, a test of my fortitude against the chaos that now defines my existence. Certainty has fled my life, save for one truth: I could not have weathered these years without the steadfastness of family and the rare friend. Disaster, real and relentless, strips away the veneer of strength.

Life, I have learned, holds no promises. Emergencies will come, like storms over an endless plain—some small, others vast. Preparation is a shield, but some tempests are too fierce to face alone.
